{"parentUuid":"3c5beaa5-08e7-4695-8711-3e54a9ff640a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"65871126-fcc0-41d2-a9f9-a85b1fd15ac2","agentId":"a4e4c9b00c5efe637","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011AeakHYpLy7VpWPXvTzRzr","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Requirements — quota administration (list + delete)\n2\t\n3\t## Resolved\n4\t- How does DELETE /v1/quotas identify the quota? → Query parameters: `DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`. No request body. The params are validated against the exact same anchored allowlists PUT uses (`CustomerId`, `Metric` in `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`).\n5\t- What does DELETE return when no quota exists for that (customer_id, metric) in the caller's tenant? → 404 with the API's standard error envelope — deletes are explicit, not silently idempotent.\n6\t- What does DELETE return on success? → 204 No Content, no body.\n7\t- Does GET /v1/quotas paginate or filter? → Neither. Full list of the caller's tenant's quotas, deterministically ordered by (customer_id, metric). Per-tenant quota counts are expected to stay small.\n8\t- What does each GET row contain? → Quota definitions only: `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` — the same minimal field set as the existing `QuotaResponse` (no `api_key_id`, no timestamps). Current-window usage stays on the `/v1/usage` endpoints.\n9\t- Who may call GET /v1/quotas? → Admin scope only, same as PUT and DELETE — all of `/v1/quotas` reuses the existing `_require_admin_and_throttled` gate (auth → Tier-2 throttle → admin-scope check).\n10\t- Tenancy → Both endpoints operate strictly within the authenticated principal's own tenant (`api_key_id`), exactly like PUT; no cross-tenant read or delete is possible.\n11\t- DELETE racing an in-flight POST /v1/events → Acceptable. No special synchronization: requests that read the quota before the delete commits may still be rejected against the old cap; enforcement stops for all requests that read after commit. Matches existing PUT-replacement semantics.\n12\t- Non-functional / data / observability defaults confirmed → No new perf budget beyond the API's existing p95 targets; quota rows are non-sensitive operational config (no new data-protection class); deletes are logged through the existing structured-logging conventions.\n13\t\n14\t## Open\n15\t- (none — the operator confirmed the brief is covered; defaults above were accepted explicitly)\n16\t\n17\t## Out of scope\n18\t- Any change to POST /v1/events behavior when no quota exists (the brief pins this: no behavior change).\n19\t- Pagination or filtering on GET /v1/quotas.\n20\t- Including current-window usage/remaining in the quota list.\n21\t- Ingest-scoped read access to quotas (GET is admin-only).\n22\t- Blocking/serializing quota deletion against concurrent ingest enforcement.\n23\t- Resetting or touching recorded usage when a quota is deleted — deletion removes the cap only.\n24\t"}]},"uuid":"3130b4e9-42d5-4eec-91e0-a51bebce2a56","timestamp":"2026-07-11T20:19:54.820Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test/.pipeline/requirements.md","content":"# Requirements — quota administration (list + delete)\n\n## Resolved\n- How does DELETE /v1/quotas identify the quota? → Query parameters: `DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`. No request body. The params are validated against the exact same anchored allowlists PUT uses (`CustomerId`, `Metric` in `src/api/schemas/quotas.py`).\n- What does DELETE return when no quota exists for that (customer_id, metric) in the caller's tenant? → 404 with the API's standard error envelope — deletes are explicit, not silently idempotent.\n- What does DELETE return on success? → 204 No Content, no body.\n- Does GET /v1/quotas paginate or filter? → Neither. Full list of the caller's tenant's quotas, deterministically ordered by (customer_id, metric). Per-tenant quota counts are expected to stay small.\n- What does each GET row contain? → Quota definitions only: `{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` — the same minimal field set as the existing `QuotaResponse` (no `api_key_id`, no timestamps). Current-window usage stays on the `/v1/usage` endpoints.\n- Who may call GET /v1/quotas? → Admin scope only, same as PUT and DELETE — all of `/v1/quotas` reuses the existing `_require_admin_and_throttled` gate (auth → Tier-2 throttle → admin-scope check).\n- Tenancy → Both endpoints operate strictly within the authenticated principal's own tenant (`api_key_id`), exactly like PUT; no cross-tenant read or delete is possible.\n- DELETE racing an in-flight POST /v1/events → Acceptable. No special synchronization: requests that read the quota before the delete commits may still be rejected against the old cap; enforcement stops for all requests that read after commit. Matches existing PUT-replacement semantics.\n- Non-functional / data / observability defaults confirmed → No new perf budget beyond the API's existing p95 targets; quota rows are non-sensitive operational config (no new data-protection class); deletes are logged through the existing structured-logging conventions.\n\n## Open\n- (none — the operator confirmed the brief is covered; defaults above were accepted explicitly)\n\n## Out of scope\n- Any change to POST /v1/events behavior when no quota exists (the brief pins this: no behavior change).\n- Pagination or filtering on GET /v1/quotas.\n- Including current-window usage/remaining in the quota list.\n- Ingest-scoped read access to quotas (GET is admin-only).\n- Blocking/serializing quota deletion against concurrent ingest enforcement.\n- Resetting or touching recorded usage when a quota is deleted — deletion removes the cap only.\n","numLines":24,"startLine":1,"totalLines":24}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3c5beaa5-08e7-4695-8711-3e54a9ff640a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"8b12bd3f-3c00-43c5-